      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/use-error-cou1",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Use error acceptance criteria — independent model review",
        "description": "An independent analyst not involved in model construction must review boundary condition definitions, material property assignments, and load application for correctness against the ASTM F1717 test configuration. All discrepancies must be resolved before acceptance."
      },
      "rationale": "An independent FDA OSEL analyst (not part of the modeling team) conducted a structured review of boundary conditions, material assignments, and load application using the USE-ERR-CHECKLIST-2023-05. Two minor annotation discrepancies (unit labels in the material property table) were identified and corrected prior to final submission. No functional modeling errors were found. Gradation 2 is met."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/model-form-cou1",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/model-form-cou1",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Model form acceptance criteria — constitutive and contact model justification",
        "description": "The constitutive model (bilinear isotropic hardening for Ti-6Al-4V, linear elastic for UHMWPE spacer) and contact formulation (augmented Lagrange, friction coefficient 0.2) must be justified by literature precedent or prior calibration studies. Alternative model forms considered and rejected must be documented."
      },
      "rationale": "Bilinear isotropic hardening parameters for Ti-6Al-4V (E=114 GPa, σ_y=880 MPa, E_tan=1.14 GPa) were sourced from ASTM E8 coupon tests on the same material lot (reported in Nagaraja et al. 2022, DOI:10.1115/1.4054898). Linear elastic UHMWPE was justified by the sub-yield strains observed in the spacer during all test configurations. Augmented Lagrange contact with μ=0.2 was validated in a prior FDA internal study (FDA-CONTACT-STUDY-2021). A penalty contact alternative was evaluated and rejected due to artificial compliance at the rod-screw interface. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/model-inputs-cou1",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/model-inputs-cou1",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Model inputs acceptance criteria — traceability to measured values",
        "description": "All geometric inputs must be traceable to CMM measurements of the physical test articles. All material property inputs must be traceable to certificated material test reports or peer-reviewed literature. Input uncertainty must be quantified and propagated to QoI uncertainty bounds."
      },
      "rationale": "Screw geometry was digitised from CMM measurements of the production 7.5 mm non-cannulated screw (CMM-RPT-2022-11, tolerance ±0.01 mm). Rod geometry was taken from engineering drawings (DePuy Synthes DWG-ROD-7p5-2022). Material properties were drawn from the material test report (MTR-TI64-LOT-2022-03) and are consistent with published values. Input uncertainty was propagated using a Monte Carlo approach (n=1000 samples, Latin hypercube sampling) and the resulting QoI uncertainty intervals are reported in UQ-RPT-2023-08. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/test-samples-cou1",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/test-samples-cou1",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Test samples acceptance criteria — traceability and representativeness",
        "description": "Test articles must be production-representative (same material lot, same manufacturing process as commercial device). Traceability records (lot number, serial number, dimensional inspection) must be available for all N=11 constructs. Sample size must be sufficient to characterise inter-specimen variability."
      },
      "rationale": "All 11 constructs used production-intent 7.5 mm non-cannulated screws from lot TI64-LOT-2022-03 and production Ti-6Al-4V rods from lot ROD-LOT-2022-07. Traceability records (lot numbers, dimensional inspection reports) are included in the submission package (TRACEABILITY-RPT-2023-02). N=11 is consistent with FDA guidance on minimum sample sizes for spinal implant bench testing and provides sufficient statistical power to estimate mean and standard deviation of each QoI. Gradation 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/test-conditions-cou1",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "The Test conditions factor is scoped out of the credibility assessment for COU1 on the following grounds. ASTM F1717 prescribes a single, fully standardised test configuration: a fixed 100 mm inter-fixture distance, a specific vertebral body surrogate geometry, and a defined quasi-static displacement rate of 5 mm/min. The standard does not permit variation in test configuration parameters as part of a conformance test, and the regulatory submission is predicated solely on demonstrating conformance with the single F1717 protocol. Because there is only one admissible test condition, the concept of 'variation in test conditions' is not applicable to this validation activity — there is no multi-condition space over which the model's sensitivity to test-condition parameters could be evaluated. Furthermore, a sensitivity analysis of the FEA model to plausible perturbations of the test-condition parameters (±5 mm inter-fixture distance, ±0.5 mm/min loading rate) was conducted as a supplementary exercise (documented in SENS-RPT-2023-10) and confirmed that QoI predictions change by less than 1.5% across the full perturbation range, well within the 10% acceptance threshold. This result supports the conclusion that test-condition variation does not meaningfully affect model credibility for this COU, and that formal assessment of this factor would provide no additional discriminatory information. The scoping decision was reviewed and approved by the credibility assessment team lead (see DECISION-SCOPE-TC-2023-11) and is consistent with the ASME V&V 40-2018 provision that factors may be scoped out when they are not relevant to the specific validation context or when the effort required for assessment is disproportionate to the credibility information gained."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/equiv-inputs-cou1",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/equiv-inputs-cou1",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Equivalency of input parameters acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Model input parameters (geometry, material properties, boundary conditions, loading) must be demonstrably equivalent to those of the physical test articles. Equivalency must be documented by direct mapping of measured specimen dimensions and material properties to model inputs, with discrepancies quantified."
      },
      "rationale": "A parameter equivalency matrix was constructed mapping each model input to its corresponding measured or specified value for all 11 test constructs (EQUIV-MATRIX-2023-06). Geometric equivalency was confirmed by comparing CMM measurements to model geometry (maximum deviation 0.03 mm, within tolerance). Material property equivalency was confirmed by comparison to MTR values (E within 0.5%, σ_y within 1.2%). Boundary condition equivalency was confirmed by comparing fixture stiffness in the model to experimentally measured fixture compliance (FIXTURE-COMPLIANCE-RPT-2023-03). Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/output-comparison-cou1",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/output-comparison-cou1",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Output comparison acceptance criteria — quantitative agreement metrics",
        "description": "QoI agreement must be assessed using the ASME V&V 40 E/uval metric. E/uval must be below 1.96 for all three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm). Additionally, percentage difference between mean FEA prediction and mean experimental result must be below 10% for each QoI."
      },
      "rationale": "E/uval values: stiffness 1.21 (pass), yield force 0.87 (pass), force at 40 mm 1.44 (pass). Percentage differences: stiffness 4.3% (pass), yield force 3.1% (pass), force at 40 mm 6.8% (pass). All three QoIs satisfy both acceptance criteria. Detailed results are in OUTPUT-COMP-RPT-2023-12. Gradation 3 achieved because the comparison used the full E/uval framework with propagated uncertainties from both the model and the experiment."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/qoi-relevance-cou1",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/qoi-relevance-cou1",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "QoI relevance acceptance criteria — linkage to clinical failure modes",
        "description": "The QoIs selected (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) must be demonstrably linked to the clinically relevant failure modes of the pedicle screw construct (fatigue fracture, permanent deformation under cyclic loading). The linkage must be documented by reference to published biomechanical literature or FDA guidance."
      },
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness governs load sharing between the implant and the healing bone graft, directly influencing fatigue life (Rohlmann et al. 2001, Spine). Yield force is the primary indicator of permanent deformation risk under intraoperative over-loading. Force at 40 mm displacement characterises post-yield energy absorption, relevant to catastrophic fracture risk. All three QoIs are explicitly cited in FDA guidance document FDA-2021-D-0785 as appropriate metrics for spinal rod-screw construct evaluation. Gradation 3 achieved because the QoI-to-failure-mode linkage is supported by both regulatory guidance and peer-reviewed literature."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/val-activity-relevance-cou1",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/val-activity-relevance-cou1",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Validation activity relevance acceptance criteria — COU fidelity",
        "description": "The validation activity (ASTM F1717 bench test) must use the same device design, same material, same assembly configuration, and same loading mode as the COU. Differences between the validation activity and the COU must be identified and their impact on credibility assessed."
      },
      "rationale": "The validation activity uses production-intent 7.5 mm non-cannulated screws assembled in the ASTM F1717 two-level construct configuration, which is identical to the COU. The loading mode (static compression-bending) directly replicates the in vivo dominant loading mode for lumbar pedicle screw constructs. The only identified difference is that the F1717 test uses a rigid vertebral body surrogate rather than cadaveric bone, which is conservative (higher stiffness surrogate loads the screw-rod interface more severely). This difference is documented in VAL-RELEVANCE-RPT-2023-13 and assessed as not materially reducing credibility for the stated COU. Gradation 3 achieved."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/decision/cou1-acceptance-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/actor/fda-osel-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment team accepts the FEA model ensemble for the stated COU (prediction of ASTM F1717 static compression-bending performance of the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw construct) on the following basis. Twelve of the thirteen ASME V&V 40 factors were formally assessed; all twelve met or exceeded their required credibility gradation. The thirteenth factor (Test conditions) was scoped out with documented rationale (single standardised ASTM F1717 protocol; sensitivity analysis confirmed QoI insensitivity to test-condition perturbations). All three QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) satisfy both the E/uval < 1.96 criterion and the < 10% percentage difference criterion against N=11 experimental constructs across two independent laboratories. The provenance chain from raw experimental data through uncertainty quantification to the E/uval metric is fully documented and traceable. The model risk level is 3 (Medium), consistent with the device classification (Class II) and the decision consequence (Medium — revision surgery, not death). No factor shortfall exists; no offset rationale is required. The assessment team concludes that the model possesses sufficient credibility for use in the regulatory submission supporting 510(k) clearance of the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw system.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
